  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal offense in the United States, and the penalties are severe. Under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA) of 1986**, the penalties for money laundering can include the following:\n\n### 1. **Criminal Penalties**\n   - **Fines**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face fines of up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n   - **Imprisonment**: Offenders can be sentenced to up to **20 years in federal prison**.\n   - **Enhanced Penalties for Certain Offenses**: If the money laundering is connected to specified unlawful activities (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, or organized crime), penalties can increase to **up to 30 years in prison** and fines of **up to $1 million**.\n\n### 2. **Civil Penalties**\n   - Civil penalties can be imposed for violations of the BSA, such as failing to report suspicious transactions or file required reports (e.g., Currency Transaction Reports or CTRs). These penalties can range from **$25,000 to $100,000 per violation**, depending on the severity and intent.\n\n### 3. **Asset Forfeiture**\n   - The government can seize and forfeit any property involved in or derived from money laundering activities. This includes bank accounts, real estate, vehicles, and other assets tied to the illegal activity.\n\n### 4. **Additional Consequences**\n   - Conviction for money laundering can result in other collateral consequences, such as loss of professional licenses, difficulty obtaining employment, and damage to reputation.\n\n### Key Statutes:\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits engaging in financial transactions with proceeds from unlawful activities to conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the funds.\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits spending or depositing more than $10,000 derived from unlawful activities.\n   - **31 U.S.C. \u00a7 5322**: Imposes penalties for willful violations of the BSA.\n\n### Aggravating Factors:\nPenalties can be more severe if the money laundering involves:\n   - Large sums of money.\n   - Repeat offenses.\n   - Involvement in international transactions.\n   - Connections to terrorism or organized crime.\n\nIf you are facing accusations of money laundering, it is critical to consult with a qualified federal criminal defense attorney to understand your rights and build a strong defense.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
